In the xOy coordinate system, there is a circular uniform magnetic field region in the second quadrant. Its radius is $l_0$, the coordinates of the center $O'$ are $(-l_0, l_0)$, and the direction of the magnetic field is perpendicular to the xOy plane pointing inward. At point P with coordinates $(-l_0, 0)$, two electrons $a$ and $b$ are injected simultaneously into this magnetic field region with equal speed $v$ but in different directions. It is known that the injection direction of electron $a$ is the $+y$ direction, and the velocity direction of electron $b$ makes an angle $\theta=\pi/3$ with the velocity direction of $a$. After being deflected by the magnetic field, electron $a$ enters the first quadrant from point $Q(0, l_0)$ on the y-axis. In the first quadrant, there exists a uniform electric field with intensity $E$ directed along the positive y-axis. Given that the mass of the electron is $m$ and the charge is $e$, and neglecting gravity, find:
(1) The magnitude of the magnetic induction $B$ of the magnetic field;
(2) The coordinate difference between electrons $a$ and $b$ upon reaching the x-axis after passing through the electric field;
(3) The time difference $\Delta t$ for electrons $a$ and $b$ to move from point P to the x-axis.
Please consider generating images during the reasoning process to help solve the problem.

As shown in the figure, on the left side of an insulated rough vertical plane MN, there exist mutually perpendicular uniform electric and magnetic fields. The electric field is directed horizontally to the right with a magnitude of E, and the magnetic field is directed perpendicular to the page outwards with a magnetic induction of B. A positively charged small slider with mass m and charge q starts sliding down along MN from rest at point A. When it reaches point C, it leaves MN and performs curvilinear motion. The distance between points A and C is h, and the gravitational acceleration is g.
[IMAGE1]
(1) Find the magnitude of the velocity vc of the small slider when it reaches point C;

(2) Find the work Wf done by the small slider against friction during the motion from point A to point C;

(3) If point D is the position where the small slider has the maximum velocity during its motion under the action of the electric force, Lorentz force, and gravity, and the magnetic field is removed when the small slider reaches point D, after which the slider continues to move to point P on the horizontal ground. Given that the velocity magnitude of the slider at point D is vD, and the time taken to move from point D to point P is t, find the magnitude of the velocity vp when the slider reaches point P.
